\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Suppose we have a device with three color sensors, whose spectral responsivities are, say, 
\begin_inset Formula $\recSens{i}(\lambda), i = 1 \ldots 3$
\end_inset

. The three sensor responses will be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\label{e8:recIll}
\recRespi{1} & = & \sum_\lambda \recSens{1}(\lambda) \ill{\lambda} \nonumber \\
\recRespi{2} & = & \sum_\lambda \recSens{2}(\lambda) \ill{\lambda} \nonumber \\
\recRespi{3} & = & \sum_\lambda \recSens{3}(\lambda) \ill{\lambda}  . 
\end{eqnarray}
\end_inset

 We can group these three linear equations into a single matrix equation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{e8:dayEst1}
\recResp = \sensorMat \illvec
\end{equation}
\end_inset

